This paper deals with the task of predicting depression levels based on audio, video, and text data. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the sub-category of Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) as it involves natural language processing techniques. Additionally, the paper proposes a novel topic modeling approach, which is a common technique used in machine learning and data mining, making it likely to belong to the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG). The paper also involves analyzing audio and video data, which suggests that it could belong to the sub-category of Computer Vision (cs.CV) or Sound (cs.SD). Finally, the paper deals with a mental health-related task, which could make it relevant to the sub-category of Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC).
